  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money laundering practices existed for centuries\n- Emerged to conceal proceeds from illegal activities\n\n2. Initial Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Legislation:\n- United States Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First comprehensive legal framework\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting and record-keeping requirements\n\n3. International Development:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n- Created 40 recommendations for global implementation\n\n4. Key Milestones:\n- US Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- US Comprehensive Crime Control Act (1984)\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)\n\n5. Post-9/11 Developments:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced financial surveillance\n- Expanded AML regulations\n- Increased international cooperation\n\n6. Recent Trends:\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Stricter international enforcement mechanisms\n\nThe legal framework continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and criminal strategies.",
